--- USER ---
it worked but now there is considerable lag. is it because of image size, how
canvas handles images, would FOB help? maybe html is just running short here?
suggestions?

--- ASSISTANT ---
The lag is almost certainly the ctx.save()/ctx.clip()/ctx.restore() being called
on every grass tile every frame. Canvas clipping is expensive — it rasterizes
the hex path as a stencil each time.

The fix is clean: use ctx.createPattern() as the fillStyle instead. The hex path
already constrains ctx.fill() to the hex shape, so no explicit clip is needed at
all. Create the pattern once, just update its transform matrix per tile to
position/scale it.

FOB/OffscreenCanvas would also help but is more complex and unnecessary here —
the pattern approach eliminates the clip overhead entirely.

[Read generate_game.py lines 1380-1395 to confirm existing clip block]

[Edit 1: after grassImg.src line, added:]
  let grassPattern = null;

[Edit 2: at top of render() function, added:]
  if (!grassPattern && grassImg.complete && grassImg.naturalWidth) {
    grassPattern = ctx.createPattern(grassImg, 'repeat');
  }

[Edit 3: replaced fill + clip block:]
  // REMOVED:
  ctx.fillStyle = t.water ? COLORS.waterFill : t.tree ? COLORS.treeFill : COLORS.tileFill;
  ctx.fill();
  if (!t.water && !t.tree && grassImg.complete && grassImg.naturalWidth) {
    ctx.save();
    ctx.clip();
    const s = HEX_H * ppu;
    ctx.drawImage(grassImg, c.x - s / 2, c.y - s / 2, s, s);
    ctx.restore();
  }
  // REPLACED WITH:
  if (!t.water && !t.tree && grassPattern) {
    const s = HEX_H * ppu;
    const sc = s / grassImg.width;
    grassPattern.setTransform(new DOMMatrix([sc, 0, 0, sc, c.x - s / 2, c.y - s / 2]));
    ctx.fillStyle = grassPattern;
  } else {
    ctx.fillStyle = t.water ? COLORS.waterFill : t.tree ? COLORS.treeFill : COLORS.tileFill;
  }
  ctx.fill();

