The root cause: ctx.save()/ctx.clip()/ctx.restore() on every grass tile every
frame forces the browser to rasterize the hex polygon as a stencil buffer each
time — that's the expensive part, not the image draw itself.

The fix replaces it with a single ctx.createPattern() call (once, on first frame
after image loads), then just setTransform per tile to position/scale it. The
hex path's ctx.fill() naturally clips the pattern to the tile shape — no
explicit clip needed at all. Pattern creation is O(1) per session, not
O(tiles × frames).

